#   SUBS-002: PATCH is unusable on any submodule (gitlink-bearing) parent (LANDED)

**HIGH ŌĆö LANDED `a31bdfcf` (2026-06-06).**  The sniff gitlink-skip was already
in place; the live bug was that `BE_PLAN_PATCH` registered `BEActSubsPatch` with
`exclude_mask = URI_AUTHORITY`, and `BEExecute` computes the slot mask *before*
`BEActResolveRemote` rewrites a transport URI to a local `?<sha>` ŌĆö so the
`be patch ssh://host?adv` form (a gitlink bump) never recursed into the sub.
Fix `beagle/DISPATCH.c` (maskŌåÆ0; the action's own guards gate it) plus
suppressing the spurious `bad ref ''` print on the empty parent-probe query in
`sniff/PATCH.c`.  Added `test/patch/28` (repro) + `test/patch/29` (control).
(Committed with `--force`: `sniff/PATCH.c` POSTCFLCT false-positive ŌĆö the marker
strings are in comments documenting the conflict-marker grammar, no real conflict.)

**HIGH ŌĆö verb effectively dead for submodule users.**  `be patch ?<branch>`
aborts with `PATCHCFLCT` (exit 157) on ANY parent whose tree contains a
`160000` gitlink, **even when the gitlink is unchanged by the patch**.  sniff
PATCH chokes on the gitlink entry (`sniff: patch: bad ref ''`,
`patch\tfailed\tvendor/sub`).  Because `BE_PLAN_PATCH` runs `BEActSniffPatch`
*before* `BEActSubsPatch`, and `BEExecute` returns on the first non-NONE error,
`BEActSubsPatch` never executes ŌĆö the gitlink-diff sub re-get recursion
(`beagle/BE.cli.c:1005-1071`) is structurally unreachable.  No `BE.dbg`/
`SUBS.dbg` recursion line ever appears; the sub never advances to the new pin.

##  Repro
 1. `be get <parent>?master` (gitlink `vendor/sub` pinned at SUB_C2).
 2. Create a parent branch `adv` whose tree bumps the gitlink to SUB_C3.
 3. On master: `be patch ?adv`.
 4. Observe exit 157 / PATCHCFLCT; `vendor/sub/core.c` stays at the C2 bytes.

Scope nuance (verified by `test/patch/28` vs `29`): the failure reproduces
when the absorbed tree **carries the gitlink as a diff entry**.  A patch that
*bumps* the gitlink (patch/28) reliably aborts.  A regular-file-only patch from
a **be-internal child branch** that shares the gitlink (patch/29) succeeds ŌĆö
the minimal squash never feeds the gitlink to sniff.  The audit's original
"even an unchanged gitlink fails" observation used a *fetched* branch whose
full tree (gitlink included) was re-applied; that construction still trips.
The core breakage is the gitlink-changed case, which is exactly what submodule
patch exists to propagate.

##  Expected
Per spec (Submodules.mkd ┬¦"TLV report aggregation"): "Patch recursion is
gitlink-diff driven (reuses GET): a sub whose applied pin differs from base is
re-got and relayed."  An unchanged gitlink must be a no-op; a changed gitlink
must trigger a sub re-get to the new pin; exit 0 when clean.

##  Actual
sniff PATCH treats the `160000` entry as a ref to resolve and fails
`bad ref ''`, turning every submodule-parent patch into a hard PATCHCFLCT.
`--nosub` changes nothing (it only guards the already-unreached
`BEActSubsPatch`).  Path-scoped patch (`be patch vendor/sub/core.c?adv`) is the
one shape that works (exit 0) because no gitlink is fed to the resolver.

##  Root cause / fix sketch
Two coupled defects: (1) sniff PATCH must SKIP `160000` gitlink entries instead
of resolving them as refs (the gitlink delta is the sub's concern, handled by
`BEActSubsPatch`'s gitlink-diff re-get, not by the parent's WEAVE merge).
(2) Ordering/aggregation: `BEActSubsPatch` should run for the gitlink even when
the parent's regular-file absorb reports a per-file failure ŌĆö or sniff should
emit a benign gitlink status so `BEExecute` does not abort.  Fix (1) first; it
likely also un-blocks (2).  See `beagle/DISPATCH.c` `BE_PLAN_PATCH` /
`BEExecute` loop and `sniff` PATCH entry handling.

##  Tests
`test/patch/28-sub-gitlink-bump-reget` ŌĆö changed pin must re-get the sub;
`WILL_FAIL` until fixed.  `test/patch/29-sub-unchanged-gitlink-ok` is a
**passing** positive control (be-internal regular-file patch over a shared
gitlink works).  Also blocks `test/all/01-subs-all-verbs`.

